      expandedNarrative: 'Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings was born in Washington, D.C. in 1896 and was a struggling newspaper writer when she bought a 74-acre orange grove in Cross Creek, Florida in 1928, sight unseen. She learned to farm, hunt, fish, and make her own liquor alongside the Cracker families who were her neighbors. The Yearling, her 1938 novel about a boy and an orphaned fawn in the Florida scrubland, won the Pulitzer Prize and became one of the most beloved American coming-of-age novels. Cross Creek, her 1942 memoir about her Florida life, prompted a lawsuit from a neighbor who recognized herself in its pages. Rawlings won the case. She is buried at Antioch Cemetery in Island Grove, Florida, the landscape she had adopted as her own.',
