      name: 'Flannery O\'Connor',
      tidbit: 'Flannery O\'Connor was diagnosed with lupus at twenty-five and told she had five years to live — she lived twelve more, writing most of her body of work on a Georgia farm while raising peacocks that she said represented the mystery of grace.',
      expandedNarrative: 'Flannery O\'Connor was born in Savannah, Georgia in 1925 and contracted lupus in 1951, forcing her to return permanently to Milledgeville and her mother\'s farm, Andalusia. Doctors predicted she had five years; she lived twelve more. Her daily routine was Mass, four hours of writing, then rest. Despite debilitating medication, she gave over sixty lectures and readings. She raised peacocks — which appear repeatedly in her fiction as symbols of divine beauty breaking into the ordinary — and corresponded prolifically with writers and theologians across the country. Everything she published, she published from that farm: two novels, two story collections, and dozens of essays. Her Complete Stories won the National Book Award in 1972, eight years after her death.',
