      expandedNarrative: 'Alice Walker was born in Eatonton, Georgia in 1944, the daughter of sharecroppers, and lost sight in one eye at eight years old in an accident with her brother\'s BB gun. She went on to win both the Pulitzer Prize and the National Book Award for The Color Purple in 1983. But one of her most consequential acts was the 1973 essay "Looking for Zora," in which she described finding Zora Neale Hurston\'s unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, having it marked, and arguing that Hurston deserved to be recognized as a foundational American writer. The essay launched the reassessment that returned Hurston\'s work to print. Walker has said the discovery felt like finding a literary ancestor who had been buried alive.',
