      expandedNarrative: 'Margaret Mitchell was born in Atlanta, Georgia in 1900 and spent a decade writing Gone with the Wind while largely housebound with a severe ankle injury. She kept the manuscript in manila envelopes scattered around her apartment and told almost no one about it. When Macmillan editor Harold Latham came to Atlanta in 1935 seeking manuscripts, she initially refused to show him hers. She relented at the last moment, handing him a stack of envelopes at the train station. The novel won the Pulitzer Prize in 1937, and the 1939 film became one of the most successful in cinema history. Mitchell never published another book. She was struck by a car and killed in Atlanta in 1949 at age forty-eight.',
