      expandedNarrative: 'James Michener was born in New York in 1907 and spent years researching Hawaii before writing a single word of the novel. Published in 1959, the year Hawaii became the fiftieth state, it traced the islands\' history from volcanic formation through Polynesian settlement, missionary influence, plantation agriculture, and the Japanese community\'s experience in World War II. For millions of Americans, it was their first sustained encounter with Hawaii\'s complexity. Michener\'s method — exhaustive research, multigenerational storytelling, deep regional history — was the same he brought to Centennial, Chesapeake, and a dozen other epics of place. He donated substantial portions of his earnings to universities and writing programs throughout his life.',
