      expandedNarrative: 'W.S. Merwin was born in New York City in 1927 and became one of the most celebrated American poets of the twentieth century, winning the Pulitzer Prize twice — in 1971 for The Carrier of Ladders and again in 2009 for The Shadow of Sirius. He was appointed U.S. Poet Laureate in 2010. But the work he may be most proud of happened on a degraded pineapple plantation on Maui\'s north shore, where he and his wife spent decades restoring native Hawaiian forest, hand-planting more than 800 species of palm trees. The Merwin Conservancy now manages the property as a botanical garden and writer\'s retreat. He died on Maui in 2019. His poetry and his land restoration project both proceeded from the same conviction: that attention is the primary moral act.',
