      expandedNarrative: 'Vardis Fisher was born in Annis, Idaho in 1895 and spent his childhood in almost complete isolation in the Snake River Canyon, miles from the nearest school. He didn\'t begin formal education until fourteen. He went on to earn a doctorate from the University of Chicago and spend his career writing one of the most ambitious projects in American letters: a twelve-volume fictional sequence tracing human spiritual and moral development from prehistoric man through the origins of monotheism. Mountain Man, a novel from outside the series, became the basis for the film Jeremiah Johnson. Fisher remained in Idaho his entire life, insisting that the American West deserved the same serious literary treatment as anywhere else.',
