      name: 'Saul Bellow',
      tidbit: 'Saul Bellow was raised in a Montreal slum by immigrant Russian parents, grew up in Chicago, and wrote the great Chicago novels — but he always insisted that Chicago made him a writer by being so genuinely, chaotically, magnificently itself.',
      expandedNarrative: 'Saul Bellow was born in Lachine, Quebec in 1915 to Russian Jewish immigrant parents and grew up on the streets of Chicago\'s Humboldt Park neighborhood. He won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1976 — at the ceremony, he was the first laureate to read from his own work. The Adventures of Augie March opens with one of the most famous sentences in American fiction and is a celebration of Chicago\'s democratic, anarchic energy. Herzog, Humboldt\'s Gift, and Mr. Sammler\'s Planet followed, each set in Chicago or among the Chicago diaspora. He taught at the University of Chicago for decades. His Nobel lecture argued that literature was essential because it was the only form that could represent the full texture of a human life.',
