      expandedNarrative: 'Kurt Vonnegut was born in Indianapolis in 1922 and was a prisoner of war in Dresden when Allied forces firebombed the city in February 1945, killing tens of thousands of people. He survived in an underground meat storage facility and emerged to help remove bodies. For twenty years he tried and failed to write about it, repeatedly describing the experience in letters as something that had paralyzed him creatively. Then Slaughterhouse-Five came out in 1969, dedicated in part to the German taxi driver who had taken him back to Dresden after the war. He described the book\'s strange time-jumping structure in its first chapter — one of the most honest accounts of creative paralysis and its release in American literature.',
