      expandedNarrative: 'Booth Tarkington was born in Indianapolis in 1869 and became one of the most celebrated American novelists of the early twentieth century, winning the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction in 1919 for The Magnificent Ambersons and again in 1922 for Alice Adams. He was a bestseller for decades, beloved for his portraits of Midwestern middle-class life and the American small town in transition. Orson Welles adapted The Magnificent Ambersons into one of his most celebrated films in 1942. Tarkington died in 1946, and his reputation faded so completely that he is now used primarily as an example of how thoroughly literary fame can evaporate. His Indiana novels remain an extraordinary portrait of a world in transition.',
