      expandedNarrative: 'Truman Capote traveled to Holcomb, Kansas in 1959 with Harper Lee to report on the murder of the Clutter family. What he planned as a magazine piece became a six-year obsession. He developed genuine relationships with the two convicted killers, Perry Smith and Dick Hickock, visiting them regularly on death row and corresponding with them for years. He attended their executions in 1965. In Cold Blood, published that same year, invented what Capote called the nonfiction novel and is widely considered the most influential piece of American literary journalism ever written. He later said that writing it cost him everything — the closeness he had cultivated with the killers, and then their deaths, broke something in him that never healed.',
