      name: 'Wendell Berry',
      tidbit: 'Wendell Berry left a prestigious teaching position at New York University in 1964, returned to his family\'s Kentucky farm, and has farmed the same land ever since — writing novels, poems, and essays that argue you cannot understand a place until you have committed your body to it.',
      expandedNarrative: 'Wendell Berry was born in Henry County, Kentucky in 1934 into a farming family that had worked the same land for generations. He left for Stanford and then New York University, where he had a tenured position, before deciding in 1964 to return to Kentucky and farm. He bought Lane\'s Landing Farm on the Kentucky River and has worked it ever since, using draft horses rather than tractors. His Port William fiction cycle — novels and stories set in a fictional Kentucky river town — is one of the great sustained meditations on community, land, and what is lost when people abandon both. His essays argue that agriculture and literature proceed from the same attention to the particular. He has never wavered from either commitment.',
