      name: 'Richard Russo',
      tidbit: 'Richard Russo set Empire Falls — his Pulitzer Prize-winning novel — in a fictional Maine mill town while actually writing about the upstate New York town where he grew up and watched the economy collapse around him.',
      expandedNarrative: 'Richard Russo was born in Johnstown, New York in 1949 and grew up watching the glove-making industry that defined his town collapse. He moved to Maine and set Empire Falls — his 2002 Pulitzer winner — in a fictional Maine mill town undergoing the same deindustrialization he had witnessed in New York. The distance gave him the perspective to write about economic devastation without sentimentality. The novel became one of the definitive portraits of working-class America\'s decline in late twentieth-century fiction. He has remained in Maine, writing novels that return again and again to the people and landscapes of small-town working-class life. His memoir Elsewhere traces his complicated relationship with his mother and his hometown.',
