      name: 'Sarah Orne Jewett',
      tidbit: 'Sarah Orne Jewett never married, never moved away from South Berwick, Maine, and spent her life writing about people and landscapes everyone else considered too small for literature — and in doing so became one of the most important American writers of the nineteenth century.',
      expandedNarrative: 'Sarah Orne Jewett was born in South Berwick, Maine in 1849 and spent most of her life there, writing stories and novels about the coastal communities of Maine\'s Down East region. The Country of the Pointed Firs (1896) is considered her masterpiece — a quietly revolutionary work that took the internal lives of rural women and aging communities entirely seriously, as worthy of literary attention as any urban drama. She was closely associated with Annie Fields, with whom she shared her life for decades in what the era called a "Boston marriage." She mentored a young Willa Cather, who said that Jewett\'s advice was the most important literary guidance she ever received. She died in 1909 after a stroke, in the house where she was born.',
