      name: 'Frederick Douglass',
      tidbit: 'Frederick Douglass taught himself to read in secret as an enslaved child in Maryland, understanding even then that literacy was the path to freedom — and the Narrative he wrote at twenty-seven became one of the most important books in American history.',
      expandedNarrative: 'Frederick Douglass was born into slavery in Talbot County, Maryland around 1818 — the exact date was unknown to him. He was separated from his mother as an infant. A slaveholder\'s wife began teaching him to read before her husband forbade it, which made Douglass more determined than ever to learn. He continued secretly, trading bread with poor white children for reading lessons. At twenty he escaped to the North. The Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass (1845) was so precise and powerful that it was used as proof he could not have been enslaved — the assumption being that no enslaved person could write that well. He revised and expanded it twice, wrote 19,000 letters in his lifetime, and lived long enough to see the Emancipation Proclamation and the passage of the Fourteenth Amendment. He is buried in Rochester, New York, where he could see the Capitol dome from his porch in Washington.',
      books: ['Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass', 'My Bondage and My Freedom', 'Life and Times of Frederick Douglass'],
