      name: 'Nathaniel Hawthorne',
      tidbit: 'Nathaniel Hawthorne was descended from a judge who sentenced women to death during the Salem witch trials — a guilt so alive in him that he changed the spelling of his name from "Hathorne" and spent his career writing fiction that circled the same moral wound.',
      expandedNarrative: 'Nathaniel Hawthorne was born in Salem, Massachusetts in 1804, descended from John Hathorne — a judge at the Salem witch trials who never expressed remorse. The guilt was so present in Hawthorne\'s imagination that he changed the spelling of his name and spent his career exploring inherited sin and the psychology of guilt in Puritan New England. The Scarlet Letter (1850) established him as the first major American psychological novelist. He spent four years at the utopian Brook Farm community, which became the setting for The Blithedale Romance. He was close friends with Herman Melville, who dedicated Moby-Dick to him. He died in 1864 on a trip to New Hampshire with former President Franklin Pierce, who was his college friend.',
