      expandedNarrative: 'Dennis Lehane was born in Dorchester, Massachusetts in 1965 and used the streets, bars, and particular social codes of that working-class Boston neighborhood as the setting for five consecutive crime novels — including Mystic River, which became a Clint Eastwood film, and Gone Baby Gone, which became a Ben Affleck film. He wrote his first novel while working as a counselor for children with special needs. Dorchester\'s loyalty codes, its violence, its insularity, and its particular relationship with grief and silence gave him everything he needed. He has since expanded his geographic range while remaining emotionally rooted in the Boston working class that shaped his moral imagination.',
