      expandedNarrative: 'Sylvia Plath was born in Boston in 1932 and grew up in Wellesley, Massachusetts. Her novel The Bell Jar, published under the pseudonym Victoria Lucas in 1963, drew on her experience winning a guest editorship at Mademoiselle magazine in 1953, her subsequent breakdown, her suicide attempt, her hospitalization, and her recovery through electroconvulsive therapy — all while her mother remained largely unaware of the full picture. She published it under a pseudonym in England partly to protect her mother. She died of suicide in London in 1963, one month after the novel\'s publication. Her poetry collection Ariel, published posthumously, is considered one of the great American poetry collections of the twentieth century.',
