      expandedNarrative: 'Elmore Leonard was born in New Orleans in 1925 but spent most of his life in the Detroit area and set much of his fiction there. He wrote Westerns for seventeen years before the market for them collapsed, then switched to crime fiction. Get Shorty, Rum Punch, Out of Sight, and dozens of other novels established him as the master of American crime fiction — a writer so good that Martin Amis called him "the greatest crime writer of our time, perhaps ever." He published his famous Ten Rules of Writing, which boil down to: leave out the parts that readers skip. He wrote until his mid-eighties and died in 2013 with an unfinished novel on his desk.',
