      expandedNarrative: 'Jeffrey Eugenides was born in Detroit in 1960 and grew up in the suburbs during the city\'s long economic decline. His debut novel The Virgin Suicides (1993), set in a Detroit suburb, was adapted into a film by Sofia Coppola. His second novel Middlesex (2002) took thirteen years to write and traces the story of Cal Stephanides, an intersex narrator, across three generations of a Greek-American family from Asia Minor to Detroit. It won the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction in 2003 and has been translated into forty-one languages. It was an Oprah Book Club selection. Eugenides has said he needed those thirteen years not because the writing was difficult but because he needed to fully understand what the book was about before he could finish it.',
