      expandedNarrative: 'Sinclair Lewis was born in Sauk Centre, Minnesota in 1885 and hated it with the specific intensity of someone who had grown up there. Main Street (1920), his portrait of Gopher Prairie\'s intellectual suffocation, was immediately recognized as a portrait of Sauk Centre and of every American small town that enforced conformity over curiosity. Sauk Centre was not pleased. In 1930, Lewis became the first American to win the Nobel Prize in Literature — which softened the town\'s view somewhat. By the time he died in 1951, Sauk Centre had embraced him: the main street is now named Sinclair Lewis Avenue. He is buried in the town he wrote about with such corrosive love.',
