      expandedNarrative: 'F. Scott Fitzgerald was born in St. Paul, Minnesota in 1896 and grew up acutely aware of his family\'s precarious position — middle class but adjacent to Summit Avenue\'s old wealth, close enough to see what money could buy and far enough away to feel its absence. He attended Princeton, dropped out, and returned to his parents\' Summit Avenue house where he rewrote the novel that became This Side of Paradise (1920). It sold immediately and made him famous. He left Minnesota and never returned, but the class anxiety of a boy who grew up watching the rich from just outside their circle runs through every novel he wrote. The Great Gatsby is, among other things, a Minnesota boy\'s meditation on what old money looks like from the outside.',
