      expandedNarrative: 'William Faulkner was born in New Albany, Mississippi in 1897 and spent most of his life in Oxford, the seat of Lafayette County, which became Yoknapatawpha County in his fiction. The Sound and the Fury, As I Lay Dying, Light in August, Absalom Absalom! — a body of work of almost incomprehensible richness, all set in the same small corner of Mississippi, all tracing the consequences of slavery and the Civil War through generations of fictional families. He received the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1949 and used his acceptance speech to insist that the writer\'s duty was to write about "the old verities and truths of the heart." He is buried in Oxford\'s St. Peter\'s Cemetery.',
