      expandedNarrative: 'Eudora Welty was born in Jackson, Mississippi in 1909 and lived in the same house on Pinehurst Street from 1925 until her death in 2001 — seventy-six years. From that single address, she produced short story collections that redefined what Southern fiction could be, a novel (The Optimist\'s Daughter) that won the Pulitzer Prize in 1973, and a memoir (One Writer\'s Beginnings) that is one of the most beautiful accounts of a literary apprenticeship ever written. She was also an accomplished photographer whose Depression-era images of Mississippi are collected at the Mississippi Department of Archives. She was one of the first literary writers to take seriously the particulars of ordinary Southern life as worthy of full artistic attention.',
