      expandedNarrative: 'Jesmyn Ward was born in DeLisle, Mississippi in 1977 and grew up in poverty on the Gulf Coast. Her brother Joshua was killed by a drunk driver in 2000 when he was nineteen. She processed that loss in her memoir Men We Reaped and in her fiction — Salvage the Bones, set during Hurricane Katrina, won the National Book Award in 2011. Sing, Unburied, Sing won it again in 2017, making her the first woman and the first Black writer to win the National Book Award for Fiction twice. She has said she writes the same story over and over — Mississippi, poverty, Black men dying young, and the women who survive them — because the story demands to be told until it is heard.',
