      expandedNarrative: 'T.S. Eliot was born in St. Louis, Missouri in 1888, descended from a long line of New England Unitarians transplanted to the Midwest. He attended Harvard, moved to England, became a British citizen in 1927, and spent the rest of his life insisting on his Englishness. He won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1948. But The Waste Land and The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock — the poems that defined literary modernism — were written by someone who had grown up watching the Mississippi and absorbing the spiritual restlessness of an America that was redefining itself. He visited St. Louis rarely after leaving and died in London in 1965.',
