      name: 'Norman Maclean',
      tidbit: 'Norman Maclean submitted A River Runs Through It to New York publishers for years and was told repeatedly that the American public had no interest in fly fishing. The University of Chicago Press published it when he was seventy-three. It has never gone out of print.',
      expandedNarrative: 'Norman Maclean was born in Clarinda, Iowa in 1902 but grew up in Missoula, Montana, where his father was a Presbyterian minister who taught his sons to fly fish on the Blackfoot River. He spent most of his career as a professor of English at the University of Chicago. A River Runs Through It, a novella drawn from his Montana boyhood, was rejected by every major New York publisher — one told him the public was not interested in fly fishing. The University of Chicago Press published it in 1976 when Maclean was seventy-three. It has never gone out of print. Robert Redford\'s 1992 film adaptation made it widely known. Young Men and Fire, his account of the 1949 Mann Gulch fire in Montana, is considered one of the great works of nonfiction.',
